Biggest problems

These are the real dragons:

Attribution

How do you prove one user’s data produced value?

Privacy

How do you let firms use data without exposing raw personal details?

Consent fatigue

Most people do not want to manage 300 micro-decisions.

Regulation

This touches securities-like dynamics, privacy law, consumer protection, labor classification, data portability.

Fraud / Sybil attacks

People will fake data if payouts exist.

Illiquidity

Not all data is valuable at all times.

Time horizon

Some data compounds value later, not instantly.

The smarter implementation

Do not launch it first as a full open market.
Launch it as:

managed data funds

Example:
	•	“AI Tutoring Fund”
	•	“Fitness Optimization Fund”
	•	“Women’s Health Research Fund”
	•	“Shopper Behavior Fund”
	•	“Local Commerce Trends Fund”

Users opt into a fund.
Companies pay to query or train on fund outputs.
Revenue gets split by contribution rules.

That is much easier than pretending everyone is day trading raw data.

Best philosophical line

If companies can compound wealth from our data, people should be able to compound ownership from contributing it.

Or even tighter:

Your data should earn like your money does.

Repo-style concept block

Name: Data Stock Market / Data Exchange
Premise: Users allocate consented data into firms, sectors, or pooled funds and receive upside proportional to the value their data helps generate.
Core Mechanic: Data allocation behaves like capital allocation.
User Object: Data wallet + consent profile + portfolio allocation.
Company Object: Data demand profile + permitted use + payout terms.
Exchange Object: Matching, valuation, attribution, privacy enforcement, payout routing.
Outputs: dividends, discounts, tokens, credits, service access, royalties.
Moat: contribution attribution + trust/consent infrastructure + pricing engine for marginal data value.
Moral Upgrade: turns silent extraction into explicit participation.
Best wedge: sector funds rather than raw open trading.

